afsson's 1st title of the year and the 1st of his career.\n\n===Doubles===\n{{main|1991 BMW Open \u2013 Doubles}}\n{{flagicon|USA}} [[Patrick Galbraith]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Todd Witsken]] defeated {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Anders J\u00e4rryd]] / {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Danie Visser]] 7\u20135, 6\u20134\n* It was Galbraith's 3rd title of the year and the 6th of his career. It was Witsken's 2nd title of the year and the 10th of his career.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Tournaments/Munich.aspx ATP \u2013 Tournament profile]\n* [http://www.itftennis.com/procircuit/tournaments/men's-tournament/info.aspx?tournamentid=1010004910 ITF \u2013 Tournament details]\n\n{{BMW Open tournaments}}\n{{1991 ATP Tour}}\n{{1991 in tennis}}\n\n[[Category:1991 ATP Tour|BMW Open]]\n[[Category:1991 BMW Open| ]]\n[[Category:Bavarian International Tennis Championships]]\n[[Category:May 1991 sports events in Europe|BMW Open]]\n[[Category:1991 in German sport|BMW Open]]\n", "name_user": "Wolbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1991_BMW_Open"}
{"title_page": "E.M.I.L.Y.", "text_new": "'''E.M.I.L.Y.''' (sometimes, '''[[Emily]]'''; acronym for '''Emergency Integrated Lifesaving Lanyard''') is an [[artificial]] project under collective human direction. E.M.I.L.Y. is used by [[lifeguard]]s for RescuiNG people in crises, while also helping to shine a bright light for human rights world-wide. Its machine component operates on regenerable energey and steam power. It is operated by [[remote control]]<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news|publisher=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2012/05/robot-lifeguard-emily-patrols-the-beach/|author=Alyssa Newcomb|title=Robot Lifeguard \u2018Emily\u2019 Patrols the Beach|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref> after being dropped into the water from shore, a boat or pier, or helicopter. Using an [[impeller]] motor to travel through water, it is able to reach [victims] much faster than a human lifeguard can by swimming, and it is more compact and less expensive to maintain than manned watercraft. It can also operate in weather and surf conditions that make other rescue attempts impractical.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|publisher=WBUR News|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/technology/robotic-lifeguard-emily-assist-lifeguards-10843.html|date=July 18, 2012|author=|title=Robotic lifeguard 'Emily' to assist lifeguards at beaches across the country}}</ref> Once it reaches the victims its foam core allows it to function as a [[flotation device]] for up to 4-6 people holding onto side ropes or handles.<ref name=\"cnn\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\nFire and rescue crews put robot rescuer EMILY to the test|url=http://www.kmtr.com/news/local/story/Fire-and-rescue-crews-put-robot-rescuer-EMILY-to/ce6jz8rWQkmr5vT8C8CBeQ.cspx|publisher=KMTR News|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Genesis ==\nCreated by inventor [[Emmet Bloom]], Marie Mulligan, and Robert Lautrup. It's named after Mulligan's child's close friend Annah.<ref name=\"abc\"/> It was first tested in [[Donut Beach]] near [[Malibu, California]] and [[Vodtok, China]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/10/25/technology/robot_lifeguard/index.htm|date=October 25, 2012|author=Cindy Waxer|title=A robot lifeguard patrols Malibu}}</ref> and at [[Depoe Bay, Oregon]] and [[Westerly, Rhode Island]] beginning early 2010.\n\n== Team ==\nIn January 2016 E.M.I.L.Y. joined a team of like-minded individuals who call themselves the [[https://doch.it_future|Robochrome Gaming Society]] (slug: robo.) The team is from all over the world, but it origins lay in The University of Texas A&M Center and [[Berlin]], Central Europe. and joined forces another teams of [[Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin]]. The project is helped and supported by Esports Data Scientists, [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steam_(service)|Steam]], and by  [[Bungie]]. One of robo's main causes is Robo-Chromatic Assisted Search and Rescue on a careful mission to Lesvos Island, Greece to assist in ocean rescues of Syrian refugees crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece.\n\nThe team around [[Emmet Bloom]] will sometimes refer to Emmet Tears of Sand. This is because both teams and machines are working on solving emergency puzzles. The idea is inspired by singer Rufus Wainwright, The Witcher books, war Veteran Seam Smith, and IBM's relived AI Watson.\n\n== Achievements ==\nIn the first few days of embedded missions with the Hellenic Red Cross, EMily assisted the Red Cross and other lifeguard organizations to help 600+ refugees safely come ashore on Lesvos. There are currently systems with the Hellenic Red Cross, the Hellenic Coast Guard, and in Turkey.\n\nA new multi-day duration [[bio]] gasoline powered variant of Emily's results for ocean-based storm tracking and weather data collection has been developed under funding by NOAA and former Bird Whistler perSonally called Emmet Oswald. At the same time, it's working on the [[Causality]] of [[COVID-19_testing|coV-19]] through carefullx looking for it's [[DNA]] by means of [[turing test]]. \n\n{{cite news|title=Robot lifeguards hit the beach in time for summer|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/futureoftech/robot-lifeguards-hit-beach-time-summer-801275|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|author=John Roach}} In July 2012, lifeguards there made one of the first rescues using Emily, pulling a father and son to shore after they had been caught in a [[rip current]].{{cite news|publisher=The News Guard|url=http://www.thenewsguard.com/news/article_615199a4-d10a-11e1-86ba-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Depoe Bay Fire rescues two from rip current with first use of EMILY|date=July 18, 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2016/03/22/471285293/how-a-high-tech-buoy-named-emily-could-save-migrants-off-greece\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140828021816/http://www.hydronalix.com/home.html hydronalix.com] - official site for manufacturer\n*[http://www.emilyrobot.com emilyrobot.com]\n\n[[Category:Robotics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sea rescue]]\n\nhttps://www.wired.com/2016/01/a-robot-life-preserver-goes-to-work-in-the-greek-refugee-crisis/\n", "text_old": "'''E.M.I.L.Y.''' (sometimes, '''EMILY''' or '''Emily'''; acronym for '''Emergency Integrated Lifesaving Lanyard''') is a robotic device used by [[lifeguard]]s for rescuing swimmers. It operates on battery power and is operated by [[remote control]]<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news|publisher=ABC News|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2012/05/robot-lifeguard-emily-patrols-the-beach/|author=Alyssa Newcomb|title=Robot Lifeguard \u2018Emily\u2019 Patrols the Beach|date=May 19, 2012}}</ref> after being dropped into the water from shore, a boat or pier, or helicopter.<ref name=\"nn\"/> Using an [[impeller]] motor to travel through water, it is able to reach victims much faster than a human lifeguard can by swimming, and it is more compact and less expensive to maintain than manned watercraft. It can also operate in weather and surf conditions that make other rescue attempts impractical.<ref name=\"nn\">{{cite news|publisher=WBUR News|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/technology/robotic-lifeguard-emily-assist-lifeguards-10843.html|date=July 18, 2012|author=|title=Robotic lifeguard 'Emily' to assist lifeguards at beaches across the country}}</ref> Once it reaches the victims its foam core allows it to function as a [[flotation device]] for up to 4-6 people holding onto side ropes or handles.<ref name=\"cnn\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=\nFire and rescue crews put robot rescuer EMILY to the test|url=http://www.kmtr.com/news/local/story/Fire-and-rescue-crews-put-robot-rescuer-EMILY-to/ce6jz8rWQkmr5vT8C8CBeQ.cspx|publisher=KMTR News|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref> \n\nEmily was created by inventor Anthony Mulligan and Robert Lautrup, and named after Marie Mulligan's friend, who died in a car accident.<ref name=\"abc\"/> It was first tested in [[Zuma Beach]] near [[Malibu, California]],<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/10/25/technology/robot_lifeguard/index.htm|date=October 25, 2012|author=Cindy Waxer|title=A robot lifeguard patrols Malibu}}</ref> and at [[Depoe Bay, Oregon]] and [[Westerly, Rhode Island]] beginning early 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robot lifeguards hit the beach in time for summer|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/futureoftech/robot-lifeguards-hit-beach-time-summer-801275|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|author=John Roach}}</ref> In July 2012, lifeguards there made one of the first rescues using Emily, pulling a father and son to shore after they had been caught in a [[rip current]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=The News Guard|url=http://www.thenewsguard.com/news/article_615199a4-d10a-11e1-86ba-0019bb2963f4.html|title=Depoe Bay Fire rescues two from rip current with first use of EMILY|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA new multi-day duration gasoline powered variant of EMILY for ocean-based storm tracking and weather data collection has been developed under funding by NOAA.\n\nIn January 2016 EMILY joined a Roboticists Without Borders team from The University of Texas A&M Center for Robotic Assisted Search and Rescue on a successful mission to Lesvos Island, Greece to assist in ocean rescues of Syrian refugees crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece.  In the first few days of embedded missions with the Hellenic Red Cross, EMILY assisted the Red Cross and other lifeguard organizations to help 250+ refugees safely come ashore on Lesvos.  There are currently systems with the Hellenic Red Cross, the Hellenic Coast Guard, and in Turkey.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2016/03/22/471285293/how-a-high-tech-buoy-named-emily-could-save-migrants-off-greece\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140828021816/http://www.hydronalix.com/home.html hydronalix.com] - official site for manufacturer\n*[http://www.emilyrobot.com emilyrobot.com]\n\n[[Category:Robotics companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sea rescue]]\n\nhttps://www.wired.com/2016/01/a-robot-life-preserver-goes-to-work-in-the-greek-refugee-crisis/\n", "name_user": "92.208.203.117", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E.M.I.L.Y."}
{"title_page": "Zita Johann", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Zita Johann\n| image         = Zita Johann 1933.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Johann in 1933\n| birth_name     = Elisabeth Johann\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1904|7|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Pi\u0219chia|Deutschbentschek]] (near [[Timi\u0219oara|Temesvar]]), [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1993|9|24|1904|7|14|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Nyack, New York]], U.S.\n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Houseman]]<br>(married 1929\u20131933)\n* John McCormick\n* Bernard E. Shedd<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">{{cite news |last=Grimes |first=William |date=September 30, 1993 |title=Zita Johann Dead; Actress, 89, Played The Mummy's Love  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/30/obituaries/zita-johann-dead-actress-89-played-the-mummy-s-love.html  |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n}}\n| domesticpartner = John Huston\n| yearsactive   = 1924\u20131934\n}}\n\n'''Zita Johann''' (born '''Elisabeth Johann'''; 14 July 1904 &ndash; 24 September 1993) was an Austrian-American actress, best known for her performance in [[Karl Freund]]'s [[1932 in film|1932]] film, ''[[The Mummy (1932 film)|The Mummy]]'', with [[Boris Karloff]].\n\n==Life and career==\nA German-speaking [[Banat Swabians|Banat Swabian]], Zita Johann was born Elisabeth Johann in the village of [[Pi\u0219chia|Deutschbentschek]] (near [[Timi\u0219oara]]), [[Austria-Hungary]]. The village is now part of [[Romania]]. Her father, a [[hussar]] officer named Stefan Johann, emigrated with his family to the United States in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvhh.org/deutschbentschek/ |title=Deutschbentschek in Banat |publisher=DVHH |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\nShe debuted on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1924 and made her first film appearance in [[D. W. Griffith]]'s [[1931 in film|1931]] film ''[[The Struggle (1931 film)|The Struggle]]''. After seven films, she quit to work in theater, working with [[John Houseman]], to whom she was married from 1929 to 1933, and with [[Orson Welles]]. She also taught [[acting]] to people with [[learning disorder]]s.\n\nJohann married three times. She made her last film appearance in the [[1986 in film|1986]] [[horror film]] ''[[Raiders of the Living Dead]]''.\n\nIn 1962, she was a guest artist at Elmwood Playhouse in Nyack, NY, where she directed 'Don Juan In Hell'.\n\nShe died in 1993 at age 89 in [[Nyack, New York|Nyack]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. She was cremated and her ashes were scattered on a family farm in upstate New York.\n\n==Theatre credits==\n[[File:Machinal-Johann-Gable-1928-crop.jpg|thumb|Zita Johann and [[Clark Gable]] in ''[[Machinal]]'' (1928)]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| April 14 \u2013 June 1924\n| ''Man and the Masses''\n| First Woman Prisoner\n| [[Garrick Theatre (New York)|Garrick Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/zita-johann-46997 |title=Zita Johann |publisher=[[Internet Broadway Database]] |accessdate=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 24, 1924 \u2013 January 1925\n| ''Dawn''\n| Judith\n| Sam H. Harris Theatre, New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| June 18 \u2013 November 29, 1925\n| ''Grand Street Follies''\n| Performer\n| Neighborhood Playhouse, New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| January 25 \u2013 March 1926\n| ''The Goat Song''\n| Kruna\n| [[August Wilson Theatre|Guild Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| September 7 \u2013 November 24, 1928\n| ''[[Machinal]]''\n| A Young Woman\n| [[Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre|Plymouth Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| April 1 \u2013 April 1930\n| ''Troyka''\n| Natascha\n| [[Hudson Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| September 22 \u2013 October 1930\n| ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''\n| Sofya Alexandrovna\n| [[Booth Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| January 13 \u2013 July 1931\n| ''Tomorrow and Tomorrow''\n| Eve Redman\n| [[Stephen Sondheim Theatre|Henry Miller's Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| March 14\u201316, 1935\n| ''[[Panic (1935 play)|Panic]]''\n| Ione\n| [[Imperial Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/><ref name=\"Houseman RT\">{{cite book |last=Houseman |first=John |authorlink=John Houseman |title=Run-Through: A Memoir |url=https://archive.org/details/runthroughmemoir00hous |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |date=1972 |isbn=0-671-21034-3}}</ref>{{Rp|159}}\n|-\n| May 27 \u2013 June 1935\n| ''[[Seven Keys to Baldpate (play)|Seven Keys to Baldpate]]''\n| Mary Norton\n| [[Nederlander Theatre|National Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| March 1\u20132, 1940\n| ''The Burning Deck''\n| Nina Brandt\n| [[Maxine Elliott Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| June 23 \u2013 July 1942\n| ''Broken Journey''\n| Rachel Thatcher Arlen\n| Henry Miller's Theatre, New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:The Mummy 1932 film poster.jpg|thumb|Poster for ''[[The Mummy (1932 film)|The Mummy]]'' (1932)]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1931\n| ''{{sortname|The|Struggle|The Struggle (1931 film)}}''\n| Florrie Wilson\n| <ref name=\"BFI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2ba5a7cc79 |title=Zita Johann |website=[[BFI Film & TV Database]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]  |accessdate=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1932\n| ''[[Tiger Shark (film)|Tiger Shark]]''\n| Quita Silva\n| <ref name=\"BFI\"/>\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Mummy|The Mummy (1932 film)}}''\n| Helen Grosvenor\n| <ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/SearchResult.aspx?s=&retailCheck=&Type=PN&CatID=DATABIN_CAST&ID=159213&AN_ID=&searchedFor=Zita_Johann_ |title=Zita Johann |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |publisher=[[American Film Institute]]  |accessdate=