mesvar]]), [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1993|9|24|1904|7|14|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Nyack, New York]], U.S.\n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Houseman]]<br>(married 1929\u20131933)\n* John McCormick\n* Bernard E. Shedd<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">{{cite news |last=Grimes |first=William |date=September 30, 1993 |title=Zita Johann Dead; Actress, 89, Played The Mummy's Love  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/30/obituaries/zita-johann-dead-actress-89-played-the-mummy-s-love.html  |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n}}\n| domesticpartner = John Huston\n| yearsactive   = 1924\u20131934\n}}\n\n'''Zita Johann''' (born '''Elisabeth Johann'''; 14 July 1904 &ndash; 24 September 1993) was an Austrian-American actress, best known for her performance in [[Karl Freund]]'s [[1932 in film|1932]] film, ''[[The Mummy (1932 film)|The Mummy]]'', with [[Boris Karloff]].\n\n==Life and career==\nA German-speaking [[Banat Swabians|Banat Swabian]], Zita Johann was born Elisabeth Johann in the village of [[Pi\u0219chia|Deutschbentschek]] (near [[Timi\u015foara|Timi\u0219oara]]), [[Austria-Hungary]]. The village is now part of [[Romania]]. Her father, a [[hussar]] officer named Stefan Johann, emigrated with his family to the United States in 1911.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvhh.org/deutschbentschek/ |title=Deutschbentschek in Banat |publisher=DVHH |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\nShe debuted on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1924 and made her first film appearance in [[D. W. Griffith]]'s [[1931 in film|1931]] film ''[[The Struggle (1931 film)|The Struggle]]''. After seven films, she quit to work in theater, working with [[John Houseman]], to whom she was married from 1929 to 1933, and with [[Orson Welles]]. She also taught [[acting]] to people with [[learning disorder]]s.\n\nJohann married three times. She made her last film appearance in the [[1986 in film|1986]] [[horror film]] ''[[Raiders of the Living Dead]]''.\n\nIn 1962, she was a guest artist at Elmwood Playhouse in Nyack, NY, where she directed 'Don Juan In Hell'.\n\nShe died in 1993 at age 89 in [[Nyack, New York|Nyack]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. She was cremated and her ashes were scattered on a family farm in upstate New York.\n\n==Theatre credits==\n[[File:Machinal-Johann-Gable-1928-crop.jpg|thumb|Zita Johann and [[Clark Gable]] in ''[[Machinal]]'' (1928)]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| April 14 \u2013 June 1924\n| ''Man and the Masses''\n| First Woman Prisoner\n| [[Garrick Theatre (New York)|Garrick Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/zita-johann-46997 |title=Zita Johann |publisher=[[Internet Broadway Database]] |accessdate=2016-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 24, 1924 \u2013 January 1925\n| ''Dawn''\n| Judith\n| Sam H. Harris Theatre, New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| June 18 \u2013 November 29, 1925\n| ''Grand Street Follies''\n| Performer\n| Neighborhood Playhouse, New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| January 25 \u2013 March 1926\n| ''The Goat Song''\n| Kruna\n| [[August Wilson Theatre|Guild Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| September 7 \u2013 November 24, 1928\n| ''[[Machinal]]''\n| A Young Woman\n| [[Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre|Plymouth Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| April 1 \u2013 April 1930\n| ''Troyka''\n| Natascha\n| [[Hudson Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| September 22 \u2013 October 1930\n| ''[[Uncle Vanya]]''\n| Sofya Alexandrovna\n| [[Booth Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| January 13 \u2013 July 1931\n| ''Tomorrow and Tomorrow''\n| Eve Redman\n| [[Stephen Sondheim Theatre|Henry Miller's Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| March 14\u201316, 1935\n| ''[[Panic (1935 play)|Panic]]''\n| Ione\n| [[Imperial Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"IBDb\"/><ref name=\"Houseman RT\">{{cite book |last=Houseman |first=John |authorlink=John Houseman 